      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "After breaking a world record the car continued racing and even competed in other classes such as AA-GT, AA-MS, and A-MS and has since been introduced into the National Corvette Museum’s vast ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "repertoire of crazy 'Vettes",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "__GHOST_URL__/articles/news/spot-the-differences-on-a-c4-zr-1/",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ". So how did this car go from the tiny 5.7-liter L83 V8 barely managing to scrape up an abysmal 205 horsepower, to this epic record-breaking monster we know today? Juris sought out the help of Mike Dorgan, Don Schellberg, Art Morrison, and Larry Kalsch to build the car as well as Bob Creitz who designed and built the 580 cubic inch fire-breather of an engine mentioned previously.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "src": "__GHOST_URL__/content/images/2021/01/Screen-Shot-2021-01-18-at-5.15.19-PM.png",
